  "local_port": 41656,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How does Swift's Dictionary compare to Objective-C's NSDictionary?",
  "response": "Here's a comprehensive comparison of Swift's Dictionary and Objective-C's NSDictionary:\n\nSwift Dictionary:\n```swift\n// Declaration and initialization\nvar swiftDict: [String: Int] = [\"key1\": 1, \"key2\": 2]\n\n// Type-safe\n// Strongly typed keys and values\nvar typedDict: [String: String] = [\"name\": \"John\"]\n\n// Mutable by default\nswiftDict[\"key3\"] = 3\n\n// Optional access\nlet value = swiftDict[\"nonexistent\"] // Returns nil, not an error\n\n// Adding/modifying\nswiftDict[\"newKey\"] = 10\nswiftDict.updateValue(20, forKey: \"existingKey\")\n\n// Removing\nswiftDict.removeValue(forKey: \"key1\")\nswiftDict[\"key2\"] = nil\n\n// Iterating\nfor (key, value) in swiftDict {\n    print(\"\\(key): \\(value)\")\n}\n```\n\nObjective-C NSDictionary:\n```objc\n// Declaration and initialization\nNSDictionary *objcDict = @{@\"key1\": @1, @\"key2\": @2};\n\n// Less type-safe\n// Can contain mixed types\nNSDictionary *mixedDict = @{@\"name\": @\"John\", @\"age\": @30};\n\n// Immutable by default\n// NSMutableDictionary for mutability\nNSMutableDictionary *mutableDict = [NSMutableDictionary dictionaryWithDictionary:objcDict];\n\n// Accessing (can raise exception)\nid value = objcDict[@\"key1\"]; // Safe\nid missingValue = objcDict[@\"nonexistent\"]; // nil\nid exceptionValue = [objcDict objectForKey:@\"nonexistent\"]; // Returns nil\n\n// Adding/modifying\n[mutableDict setObject:@10 forKey:@\"newKey\"];\n\n// Removing\n[mutableDict removeObjectForKey:@\"key1\"];\n\n// Iterating\n[objcDict enumerateKeysAndObjectsUsingBlock:^(id key, id obj, BOOL *stop) {\n    NSLog(@\"%@: %@\", key, obj);\n}];\n```\n\nKey Differences:\n\n1. Type Safety\n- Swift Dictionary: Strongly typed, compile-time type checking\n- Objective-C NSDictionary: Weakly typed, runtime type checking\n\n2. Mutability\n- Swift Dictionary: Mutable by default with 'var', immutable with 'let'\n- Objective-C: Immutable by default, requires NSMutableDictionary for changes\n\n3. Initialization\n- Swift: More concise, literal syntax\n- Objective-C: Requires method calls or literal syntax with @ symbol\n\n4. Nil Handling\n- Swift: Safely returns nil for non-existent keys\n- Objective-C: Returns nil, but can potentially raise exceptions\n\n5. Performance\n- Swift Dictionary: Generally faster, value-type semantics\n- Objective-C NSDictionary: Reference-type, slightly more overhead\n\n6. Key Constraints\n- Swift: Keys must be Hashable\n- Objective-C: Keys can be any object conforming to NSCopying\n\nExample of Hashable Requirement in Swift:\n```swift\n// Custom type as dictionary key\nstruct Person: Hashable {\n    let name: String\n    let age: Int\n}\n\nvar peopleDict: [Person: String] = [\n    Person(name: \"John\", age: 30): \"Employee\"\n]\n```\n\nPerformance Optimization in Swift:\n```swift\n// Reserving capacity for better performance\nvar largeDict = [String: Int](minimumCapacity: 1000)\n```\n\nBridging Between Swift and Objective-C:\n```swift\n// Swift to Objective-C\nlet swiftDict: [String: Any] = [\"key\": \"value\"]\nNSDictionary *objcDict = swiftDict as NSDictionary\n\n// Objective-C to Swift\nNSDictionary *objcDict = @{@\"key\": @\"value\"};\nlet swiftDict = objcDict as? [String: Any]\n```\n\nBest Practices:\n1. Use Swift Dictionary when possible\n2. Prefer type-safe dictionary declarations\n3. Use optional binding or nil-coalescing for safe access\n4. Consider performance with large dictionaries\n\nRecommendation:\n- In Swift projects, use Swift's native Dictionary\n- When working with Objective-C frameworks, use bridging as needed\n\nThe Swift Dictionary provides a more modern, type-safe, and performant approach to key-value storage compared to the Objective-C NSDictionary.",
